More you must not ask for the next two days.<br />
This, if it happens, will take place on the third day.<br />
You will know about it very soon after,<br />
But say nothing, nothing whatever,

[p. <i>155</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00151&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

<i>Note:</i> After this the time sequence as noted in the diary, becomes
rather confused. But I remember that I expected the disaster
connected with A--&apos;s brother, if it happened at all, to happen on
Saturday. Later, as I received more detailed information from
the Voice, I expected it to happen on Sunday night. Between
Thursday and Saturday, when I could say nothing to anyone of
my fears, the anxiety and tension increased.


<i>Diary continued:</i>


<i>Friday morning, July 6</i>. Instructions--get off teaching, walk to the
village and buy some coffee.


<i>10.5</i>. Set out on foot to buy coffee, told to walk slowly. Took half
an hour. Think I was sent out to miss something that happened in the
School at 10.20. All this is tiring, torturing, but I do it. Return. Told
now to make a cup of coffee and go slowly. Right. <i>See no one</i>. Relax
for a little. Smoke.


<i>11.10</i>. Two lines:
<blockquote>
<p>
Why do you weep, child, why do you weep?<br />
There is nothing to cry for.
</p>
</blockquote>


Why do you weep, child, why do you weep?<br />
There is nothing to cry for.


<i>11.20</i>. Message tells me someone tall, with a stammer, will come to
me, tells me what to say. Tells me to stay here. Tells me to wait.
It is so hard to wait. I feel lonely and frightened and weak.


<i>4.30</i>. Went on waiting all these hours, nothing happens. I get more and
more anxious. At about 3 o&apos;clock try to get another message. Have
a kind of convulsion, mind goes blank, can&apos;t think, can&apos;t believe,
can&apos;t do anything. Only the phrase, ‘body trodden by the bird’, over
and over. Then I fall asleep for about half an hour and wake up again
feeling calm, though tired and rather blank. Still nothing happens. I
suppose I must just wait until something does. Ate some bread out of
turn (i.e. without permission from the Voice) for which I hope I shall
be forgiven. I really thought I was going out of my head. That at least
is averted, for the time being anyway. Still don&apos;t know what to think
or what to believe.


<i>8.30</i>. Still nothing happens, except that after supper, when I suddenly
decided to go and see W-- and try to explain to him what was

[p. <i>156</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00152&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

‘The bird treads your body’<br />
This was to give you<br />
A rest from the heavy load<br />
Which you are carrying.


<i>Note:</i> ‘Fit’ is an inadequate word to describe this experience,
which later, in a great variety of forms, I became very familiar
with. It was really a series of convulsive movements like exercises
and massage, mixed up with a great many ritualistic and symbolic
movements and repetitions of numbers carried out compulsively.
I came to think that it had a therapeutic effect on various nerve
centres. I have tried to describe it in more detail later in this book.
At this time I associated it with the Holy Ghost and regarded it as
a ritual cleansing and strengthening.


<i>Diary continued:</i>


<i>Saturday morning, July 7</i>. I hope I am doing the right thing. I feel
more and more a heavy burden of responsibility, but also that I am
being helped and guided. Again it all centres round A--, and it
must be quite dreadful, for though I don&apos;t yet know what it is, it
makes me weep as I write this. I think it is some form of diabolical
torture connected with the rabbit.


<i>Note:</i> Some days before I had noticed a young rabbit being kept
in a box by someone in A--&apos;s classroom. I thought now that A--
would get hold of this rabbit and use it in the same way as he had
the hen, by tying it up and throwing his knife at it (I had no
direct evidence for any of this except a previous statement from
A--that he had been torturing hens). I thought that he
would use the rabbit as a male substitution symbol, as the hen
was a female symbol. The idea is not perhaps so wildly fanciful
if the reader knows that A-- had a bitter feud against the school
chaplain, whom he loathed and detested and that the chaplain&apos;s
nickname was ‘Bunny’. One very strange circumstance is that

[p. <i>157</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00153&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

I remember him telling me that he had a tennis ball fastened
to a length of cord and hung from a beam, and that this he
belaboured savagely with a racket for hours on end. Inside the
tennis ball was God, and thus A-- got some of his own back for
God&apos;s cruelty to him. I could not laugh at such a story, I found it
terrifying.


<i>Diary continued:</i>


I feel I must keep in seclusion as much as I possibly can, at least till A--
has gone home. <i>I must not see him or talk to him</i>.


<i>12.30</i>. Somewhere in the wilds in my faithful car, I think I must get
back to school at about 1.45. Get some petrol as I go back
When I get back, I must go up to my room, re-read the instructions,
perhaps write them out in the book. I think I may hear about A--
maybe at 5 o&apos;clock. If so I shall go to him and take the poems with me.
If necessary get Dr H--. Meanwhile wait. God give me strength. Keep
away from people.


<i>Later: 1 o&apos;clock</i>. My instructions are changed. I am told to go straight
back to school and to look at the Lower Fifth papers on the table.
(These were exercises and essays set them as work in my absence.)

[p. <i>158</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00154&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

(1) No or (the answer is No).


(2) Let&apos;s eat this food.


That seems quite explicit. We have got to go through with it. God
help us. I think I shall have to be out of my room for a little while. I
shall go up to my bedroom and lock the door, till I am told to come
down.


Another sentence in A--&apos;s papers, which is not part of the exercise,
but is written in capital letters at the bottom:


YE FOOLS AND BLIND!


<i>1.30</i>. I have told Dr H-- as much as I was permitted and he will be
ready if needed.


<i>Note:</i> I think that I paid one of my regular visits to Dr H-- that
morning and in the course of the interview had hinted that I was
afraid that a dangerous crisis was approaching in A--&apos;s life and
had asked him to be ready that evening in case anything happened.
Dr H-- naturally wanted to know more but when I told
him that I had been absolutely forbidden by the Voice to say any
more at present, he accepted the fact, and told me where I could
reach him on the telephone if necessary.


<i>Diary continued:</i>


A fourth sentence in A--&apos;s exercise is pointed out to me.


I start work at 8 o&apos;clock.


Does this mean what I think it does ? If so I must make arrangements
to stop it. Dr H---&apos;s telephone numbers: 7 o&apos;clock to 8 o&apos;clock.
T-- 3958. 9 p.m. onwards, H-- 234. ‘You are not alone,’ said Dr
H--. More and more I feel this. Alone I could not do it.


<i>1.25</i>. At 1.35 He (the Voice) says ‘Finish the cigarette, then you may
go down. (I was locked in my bedroom.) Copy in the poems. Do
nothing in a hurry. I will look after you.’


<i>9 p.m</i>. Nothing happens. I am very tired and I am afraid, afraid of the
strain of this. I have been expecting something since 8 o&apos;clock. Have
I got the days wrong or is it all just a disordered mind? I just can&apos;t
believe that. Another day of this kind of thing will finish me. I don&apos;t
know what to do. I shall try to get some rest. If anything did happen

[p. <i>159</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00155&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

<i>12 o&apos;clock Midnight</i>. There comes this message:
<blockquote>
<p>
‘In a pit of serpents,<br />
Buried in the garden<br />
Under the apple tree!<br />
Tell H-- about it,<br />
Ring up in the morning.’
</p>
</blockquote>


‘In a pit of serpents,<br />
Buried in the garden<br />
Under the apple tree!<br />
Tell H-- about it,<br />
Ring up in the morning.’


<i>Later:</i>
<blockquote>
<p>
‘In a little blue box,<br />
Colour of a hyacinth,<br />
He has buried<br />
Some kind of poison.<br />
His poor brain<br />
Is afflicted with madness.<br />
He will dig it up,<br />
