[p. <i>160</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00156&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

<i>Diary continued:</i>


<i>Sunday, July 8. 6.30 a.m</i>. I wake up and I begin to realize almost
the whole chain of events and I weep very bitterly for my child A--
given over to darkness and devils. I know that what I always feared
is true. He is going mad. Now I must get up and be quite sure that I
get all the evidence and that I ring up Dr H-- early enough to be
sure of getting him. <i>I must see him this morning</i>. The whole thing
becomes more and more strange and it also gets very terrible. The
New Messiah. The Avenger. This is what A-- called himself. I didn&apos;t
take it seriously then.


Somewhere in his room is a book or diary of his plans and thoughts,
all written down.

[p. <i>161</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00157&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

<i>On no account must I see him</i>. He&apos;ll know at once that I know and
that I know everything.


He will first take the poison and give some to his mother (in sweets?
sugar?) then he will try to kill his brother. O God!


<i>Later</i>. ‘Look at his essay.’ I look at it. It is haphazard. The
quotations from the Bible, an odd mixture. Two opposing forces at
work. Again at the end in a totally different writing the word
‘armageddon’. The end of the world. The end of A--&apos;s world
anyway.


Look at the violent change in his feeling for his mother. Now
she is a bitch. (That&apos;s what he called her to me.) He loathes her.
He hates her. He has been torturing hens. The hen has been symbolizing
his mother up to now. He told me he had been torturing them.
Last time I saw him he told me he had given it up. ‘It was’, he said, ‘a
rather crude way of doing things.’ Now he has turned his attention
to his real mother.


The trip to the city represents a kind of dedicated journey to
make ready for the sacrifice. A-- thinks he is God or the Devil, the
only true God. His hatred against the chaplain and any of God&apos;s
official representatives is bitter and intense and <i>it has been growing
worse and worse</i>.


The trip to the city which I financed (God help me) was to get ready
for the sacrifice. I am right. I know it. It will take place today. ‘I
start work at eight o&apos;clock!’


It must surely, somehow, be prevented, or is it all wild, insane
delusions? This is my real difficulty.


It is unthinkable that his mother should die and that he should
take poison, but the poem specifically says that if he does not heed
the warning, his brother will be injured and disaster fall upon him,
<i>and it cannot be prevented</i>. Must hope for more light on this soon.


<i>9.15</i>. I ring up Dr H-- and make an appointment. Thank God for
him. Oh, poor A--, so lost, so lost.


<i>10 o&apos;clock</i>. Another message.


‘Tell H-- when he gets there (A--&apos;s home)<br />
To go into the garden<br />
By the little gothic gate.<br />
Tell him he will find the child<br />
Under the apple tree<br />
Digging up his treasure.<br />
Tell him to speak to him<br />
Gently, secretly,<br />
No one else knowing,

[p. <i>162</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00158&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

<i>Note:</i> Here the diary ends. I remember that I rang up Dr H-- on
Sunday morning and asked him as a matter of the gravest urgency
to make an appointment for me to see him. He agreed to see me
almost at once. I got into my car to go into the town to keep the
appointment, and as I was turning out of the school drive, I
almost ran into A--, who was coming in on his bicycle. The sight
of him was a very great shock to me. Since Thursday, when I had
given him the message, I had been strictly enjoined by the Voice
to have no contact whatever with him, and this chance meeting
seemed to me extremely ominous. Fortunately the car was still
moving and I was able to avoid having to do more than raise my
hand in greeting as we passed, but I felt very much frightened and
shaken as I proceeded on my way. I showed the Doctor all the
messages and my conclusions recorded in the diary. I told him
that I believed that A-- was out of his mind and that he must go
out on some pretext to the child&apos;s home that evening before
eight o&apos;clock, as instructed in the message, prepared if necessary
to take action to prevent the terrible occurrences which I
feared.


Dr H-- did not attempt to argue with me. He seemed quite
prepared to believe that I might very well be right, and to
act on my foreknowledge. He told me that he was himself very
worried about A--, and what to do with him if he turned violent.
He agreed to go out to Tolland that evening and to have some

[p. <i>163</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000697830-I00159&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

For this I shall never cease to be grateful to him. I do not know
what I should have done, if he had not co-operated.

